at the local maximum (perturbative vacuum) . We don't
make this choice here; in fact, for all , the potential
() is zero at the local minimum .
 


Lower-dimensional spacetimes and double lumps 


In this section, we will argue that lumps of the closed tachyon 
represent flat spacetime extended along the lump's worldvolume
only. Those are therefore spacetimes of lower dimensions.

 
Let us first write the equations of motion derived from ()
 
For finite , these equations are very hard to solve
analytically. We will therefore start our discussion by setting . 
Recall that  is proportional to the string coupling.
In the limit   the first equation 
in () determines a classical closed string background, 
the second equation then tells the field  how to propagate in that 
background. The back-reaction is neglected in this limit.
For fields depending only on the  spatial coordinates  
the equations then take the form  
p^-1 4  _x^2  &=& ^p^2  

